The treadmill died, and instead of hauling it to the curb I had a multimeter and a hunch — and the hunch was right, one bulged capacitor giving itself away as a dead reading. Three things lined up there: the broken machine that needed me, the meter that turned a mystery into a measurement, and the professor years ago who taught me how to use one and how to think like the other. You don't always get to thank the person whose lesson saved your Saturday, but I know exactly whose it was.
